[[Image:Descendants of Izanagi and Izanami.svg|thumb|right|250px|Kami born from Izanagi and Izanami ([[Media:Descendants of Izanagi and Izanami.svg|View in SVG format (supported browsers only)]])]] : '''Mikahayahi''' '''no Kami''' (甕速日神) is a deity in {{ill|Japanese mythology|ja|日本神話}}, born during the {{ill|kami birth (Shinto)|ja|神産み}} when {{ill|Izanagi|ja|イザナギ}} decapitated {{ill|Kagutsuchi|ja|カグツチ}}. Mikahayahi no Kami emerged from the blood that splattered onto rocks from the base of the {{ill|Totsuka-no-Tsurugi|ja|十束剣}} known as "{{ill|Ame-no-ohabari|ja|天之尾羽張}}."
According to the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}}'', Mikahayahi no Kami is considered an ancestor of {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|武甕雷男神}}. However, the text also states that {{ill|Hisahayahi no Kami|ja|樋速日神}}, Mikahayahi no Kami, and Takemikazuchi were born simultaneously. [[ja:甕速日神]] In the ''{{ill|Un'yōshi|ja|雲陽誌}}'', a regional record compiled during the Edo period in the {{ill|Matsue Domain|ja|松江藩}}, the section on {{ill|Matsuzaki Shrine|ja|松崎神社}} mentions, "The ancestral deity of this shrine is called Mikahayahi, the god of the stars."<ref>{{cite book|editor=Ashida Ikuto |title=Great Japanese Gazetteer Series|volume=Vol. 27|publisher=Yuzankaku |year=1930 |chapter=Un'yōshi Volume 1, Shimane District|section=Matsuzaki Shrine|page=24|doi=10.11501/1194083|url={{NDLDC|1194083/19}} }} ({{ill|National Diet Library Digital Collections|ja|国立国会図書館デジタルコレクション}})</ref>
