'''Mikahayahi''' '''no Kami''' (甕速日神) is a deity in {{ill|Japanese mythology|ja|日本神話|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese mythology|qq=}}, born during the {{ill|kami birth (Shinto)|ja|神産み|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kami birth (Shinto)|qq=}} when {{ill|Izanagi|ja|イザナギ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izanagi|qq=}} decapitated {{ill|Kagu-tsuchi|lt=Kagu-tsuchi|lt=Kagutsuchi|ja|カグツチ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kagutsuchi|qq=}}. Mikahayahi no Kami emerged from the blood that splattered onto rocks from the base of the {{ill|Totsuka-no-Tsurugi|ja|十束剣|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Totsuka-no-Tsurugi|qq=}} known as "{{ill|Ame-no-ohabari|ja|天之尾羽張|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ame-no-ohabari|qq=}}."

According to the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}'', Mikahayahi no Kami is considered an ancestor of {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|武甕雷男神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takemikazuchi|qq=}}. However, the text also states that {{ill|Hisahayahi no Kami|ja|樋速日神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hisahayahi no Kami|qq=}}, Mikahayahi no Kami, and Takemikazuchi were born simultaneously.

In the ''{{ill|Un'yōshi|ja|雲陽誌|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Un'yōshi|qq=}}'', a regional record compiled during the Edo period in the {{ill|Matsue Domain|ja|松江藩|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsue Domain|qq=}}, the section on {{ill|Matsuzaki Shrine|ja|松崎神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsuzaki Shrine|qq=}} mentions, "The ancestral deity of this shrine is called Mikahayahi, the god of the stars."<ref>{{cite book|editor=Ashida Ikuto |title=Great Japanese Gazetteer Series|volume=Vol. 27|publisher=Yuzankaku |year=1930 |chapter=Un'yōshi Volume 1, Shimane District|section=Matsuzaki Shrine|page=24|doi=10.11501/1194083|url={{NDLDC|1194083/19}} }} ({{ill|National Diet Library Digital Collections|ja|国立国会図書館デジタルコレクション|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/National Diet Library Digital Collections|qq=}})</ref>

